<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n41106d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n41" href="#n41106d">N41 (VI.B.33)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n41all.htm#n41106d"> 106(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bath allusions / accompany acts / of 3 W.</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Appendix: Variants and Analogues [&hellip;]</font> by W.A. Clouston <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> One day this <mark>trefoil</mark> of roguery met at the public <mark>bath</mark>, and, according to their homogeneous nature they intermingled <mark>as intimately as the comb with the hair</mark>; they tucked up their garments of amity to the waist of union, entered the tank of agreement, seated themselves in the hot-house of love, and poured from the dish of folly, by means of the key of hypocrisy, the water of profusion upon the head of intercourse; they rubbed with the brush of familiarity and the soap of affection the stains of jealousies from each other&apos;s limbs. After a while, when they had brought the pot of concord to boil by the fire of mutual laudation, they warmed the bath of association with the breeze of kindness, and came out. <small> Richard F. Burton, trans. <a name="RBTE3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RBTE3"><cite title="source">Supplemental Nights to the Book of the Thousand Nights and a Night</cite></a> (n.d.) II, 329-30</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c06200b" href="c06all.htm#c06200b">VI.C.06:200(b)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
